table-0751-209.caption: Timeline
data: In addressing the appreciation of Japanese yen, BOJ began to ease the monetary policy, slashed the official discount rate from 5.0% to 3.0%. Japanese yen touched a new high against the U$ (154.11¥/U$) in August before settled down at 162.13¥/U$ in December. Nikkei 225 strengthened further from 13,024 (January 6, 1986) to 18,821 (December 1, 1986). Average land prices (per 1sq. metre) in Tokyo residential areas recorded an increase of 45% (compared to 1985), while average land prices (per 1sq. metre) in Tokyo commercial districts jumped approximately 122% (compared to 1985). Land prices in Tokyo industrial site jumped about 14%. (per 1sq. metre) Commercial land prices (per 1sq. metre) in Osaka rose 35% compared to the previous year.

Japanese yen strengthened to 123.16¥/U$ by November before weakened slightly to 123.63¥/U$ in December. Nikkei 225 broken 30,000 level marks and recorded a new high 30,159 in December 1, 1989. Asset prices growth in Tokyo metropolis began to stagnant especially in residential areas and commercial districts. Lands in certain wards in Tokyo metropolis began to drop. Other urban land in Greater Tokyo area remained in upward trend. Urban land in Osaka, Kyoto, Aichi (in Nagoya) and Hyogo (in Kobe) prefecture were largely unaffected by the situation by the Tokyo counterparts.

Consumption tax was introduced in Japan around April 1989. BOJ tightened the monetary policy by hiking the official discount rate from 2.5% to 4.25% by the late December 1989. Japanese Yen fell against U$, fell as low as 145.06¥/U$ by September. Nikkei 225 continued to be bullish, as Nikkei 225 touched historical all-time high of 38,957.44 in December 29, 1989. Land prices crashed in Tokyo metropolis as residential land on average 1 sq. metre declined by 4.2%, while land prices in commercial districts and industrial site in Tokyo metropolis remained stagnant. Adjacent prefecture especially Kanagawa prefecture also began to be affected due to its geographical location to Tokyo metropolis. In Yokohama (Kanagawa), land prices in residential area were either stagnant or dropped slightly compared to 1988. All other major urban land in Japan were remained unaffected by the asset collapse over Tokyo.

BOJ continued to tighten the monetary policy by pushing the official discount rate from 4.25% to 6.00%. Japanese yen weakened to as low as 158.50¥/U$ by April but began to strengthen in second half of 1990; touched as high 129.01¥/U$ by November. Nikkei 225 dropped sharply from 37,189 (January 1, 1990) to 23,849 (December 3, 1990), lost over 35% in value in 1990. Asset prices in Tokyo metropolis stabilized from moving downwards. All other major urban land in Japan remained in upward trend.

Japanese yen resumed the upward trend against U$, strengthened back to 129.07¥/U$ by December. Nikkei 225 dropped to 22,984 in December 2, 1991 compared to 23,293 in January 4, 1991. Land prices (residential, commercial and industrial site) in Tokyo fell sharply. All other major urban land prices in Japan grew modestly or stagnant. Towards the end of the year, most urban land prices fell into negative territory.

Ride located in Hanna-Barbera Land This was a kiddie version of the Tumble Bug ride. It was removed to make way for the Nickelodeon Universe expansion.
Cuddle Up was a Cuddle Up/Crasy Daisy type ride located in Coney Island (now Coney Mall).
A flat ride which consisted of rotating barrel-shaped cars. Replaced with landscaping behind Viking Fury.
You could take a ride on an elephant located in the Wild Animal Safari section of the park.
Small water raft ride in Hanna-Barbera Land themed to forest animals.
Removed in 2005 as a part of the Hanna-Barbera Land removal for Nick Universe.
Another antique car ride, this one intertwined with the previously mentioned Les Taxis. The Auto Livery last operated in 1997, but the ride was not removed until 2004 along with Les Taxis.

Dark ride themed by R and R and animatronics done by AVG Inc. A behind the scenes tour of an abandoned theater, where phantoms either helped or taunted riders. Used the omnimover system now employed by Boo Blasters on Boo Hill.
A ride where passengers lined a circular room. As the ride began to spin, the floor descended several feet, leaving riders held against the wall by centrifugal force. Removed for Festhaus.

A cable car skyride that took passengers from Oktoberfest (where Adventure Express' entrance is today), over the International Street fountains, to Hanna Barbera Land. The Station house still remains today as a merchandise store. Relocated from Coney Island Ohio (1965–1971).

Yet another sports car ride, this one was located in Hanna Barbera Land. It was removed after the 1994 season, to make room for Nickelodeon Splat City (today's Nickelodeon Universe). Formerly known as Marathon Turnpike, Speed Buggy Turnpike.
